         <abstract>
            <p>The author develops a simple rule for discounting cash flows when the simple capital asset pricing model holds in every period, and when an investment's cash flows are linear in each period's market return (in a general sense). The unconditional expected cash flow, the beta of the cash flow's value, or the expected market return are not needed. This method works for cash flows that follow normal distributions, lognormal distributions, and even more general distributions, but it does not work for nonlinear functions of individual market returns like those provided by options.</p>
         </abstract>
